headClientCertificateCollection ? 
I am aware of the problems with the privilege registry but for now, I think having these follow their schemas makes the most sense (I suspect this is  a no-op.)

> headClientCertificateCollection ? 

Because this is a ContainsResource=True in the schema, i believe they take on the permissions of the resource they're contained within, at least I think that's what we've done other places.

Even if they didn't, we don't really have a provision for returning part of a resource and marking certain properties unavailable, so at least we're internally consistent.

> I am aware of the problems with the privilege registry but for now, I think having these follow their schemas makes the most sense (I suspect this is  a no-op.)

the above makes it sound like I care a lot more than I do.  If you still think that with ContainsResource=True, these should be headCertificateCollection (because that's what they are, ClientCertificateCollection is not a type), I can make that change, I'm not sure it's correct for those using Operator, but those that user Operator can tell us it's broken.

I use admin and certificatecollection and certificate are in the privilgeregistry already, so that change doesn't actually effect me either way.

No, this would be an implementation error, because the json key is set by the programmer, not the user.  This was just so that.

I think certs/authority object path meant for CA certificates right?
ldap client certificate place at object path
/xyz/openbmc_project/certs/client/ldap
similarly certificate-manager may need to host these client certificates at similar path 
/xyz/openbmc_project/certs/client/<>

> I think certs/authority object path meant for CA certificates right?

That's not what's in the existing code in Manager, and this code does seem to work.

> ldap client certificate place at object path
> /xyz/openbmc_project/certs/client/ldap
> similarly certificate-manager may need to host these client certificates at similar path 
> /xyz/openbmc_project/certs/client/<>

Nothing changes about this compared to TrustStore, which uses the existing paths.  If we wanted to change those, we could, but that IMO isn't what this patch is trying to do.  It's trying to bring up ClientCertificates, using the existing flow that already exists.

Yes i understand, but if we look at certificate-manager design CA authority certificate and client certificate handled differently.

https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/tree/master/yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/Certs#signed-certificate-upload-design-flowpre-generated

as per certificate-manager design
"The URI /xyz/openbmc_project/certs/authority/truststore maps to instance of the certificate application handling Certificate Authority certificates"
so I was thinking these MFA client certificates needs to be handled differently than CA certificates in certificate-manager otherwise this commit looks good.

> "The URI /xyz/openbmc_project/certs/authority/truststore maps to instance of the certificate application handling Certificate Authority certificates"


Isn't that what this property is?  It's the list of certificates used for client authentication (ie the certificate authority).

As per my understanding there two categories, CA root certificates and client certificates.
if we are hosting these certs at "/xyz/openbmc_project/certs/authority/truststore" is there any way to know which is CA certificate or client certificates?
suppose if we configure both LDAP certificates  and MFA client certificates 
there should be way to differentiate

> As per my understanding there two categories, CA root certificates and client certificates.
> if we are hosting these certs at "/xyz/openbmc_project/certs/authority/truststore" is there any way to know which is CA certificate or client certificates?
> suppose if we configure both LDAP certificates  and MFA client certificates 
> there should be way to differentiate

They're all root certificates.  If phosphor-certificate-manager wanted to, it could have methods for getting certificates by an ext property, which would allow us to filter down further, but this doesn't seem terribly useful.  It seems relatively unlikely that a user is going to set up both LDAP and mutual TLS, so in practice we'd likely have one root certificate, and this issue wouldn't pop up.

FWIW, I'm open to looking into changes into that area, but I think the development order should go:
1. Implement ClientCertificateCollection GET, using existing certificate methods.
2. Implement ClientCertificateCollection POST, using existing certificate methods.
(at this point, the base use cases work, and we can test compliance).
3. Implement support in phosphor-certificate-manager for filtering client certificates.
4. Move bmcweb over to the new certificate filtering API (which should be a simple change).

Seem reasonable?

same here, I think hosting client certificates at "xyz.openbmc_project.Certs.Manager.Authority.Truststore" does not look right.
as per my understanding authority D-bus meant for CA certificates management
It's what's already used currently, so I'm not sure what more we can do.

Doesn't /redfish/v1/AccountService/MultiFactorAuth also need to be implemented?

Something doesn't add up here or my understanding of Redfish is off. 
I thought all segments in a path should map to a schema. 
So you could go to a Redfish Route and walk backwards to /redfish/v1/
E.g.
/redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/Entries/141 <- LogEntry 
/redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/Entries/ <- LogEntryCollection
/redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/ <- LogService 
/redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/ <- LogServiceCollection
...

> Doesn't /redfish/v1/AccountService/MultiFactorAuth also need to be implemented?
> 
> Something doesn't add up here or my understanding of Redfish is off. 
> I thought all segments in a path should map to a schema. 
> So you could go to a Redfish Route and walk backwards to /redfish/v1/
> E.g.
> /redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/Entries/141 <- LogEntry 
> /redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/Entries/ <- LogEntryCollection
> /redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/ <- LogService 
> /redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/ <- LogServiceCollection
> ...


This is one of the weird things in the redfish spec that I've complained to them before as inconsistent.  Because "MultiFactorAuth" is a ComplexType, and not a schema object, it counts as a fragment.  In theory, you'd never go Schema -> Complex -> Schema..... yet there's a couple places they do, and I think we decided that this is the right behavior to not have a handler for the URI you noticed, because /redfish/v1/AccountService/MultiFactorAuth technically doesn't exist, and there's no odata.type we could put there.

You're not wrong..... this stuff is confusing, but based on my understanding (which very much could be wrong) this is correct.

Your comment below about not seeing the /redfish/v1/AccountService/MultiFactorAuth/ClientCertificate URL is explained by ClientCertificate being a ComplexType.

Redfish pointed my at https://www.dmtf.org/sites/default/files/standards/documents/DSP0266_1.20.0.html#resource-uri-patterns-annotation
Redfish issue 6073 for anyone with access. 
This looks correct based on their mockup schemas.

Redfish is a hypermedia API. 
I think you need a /redfish/v1/AccountService/MultiFactorAuth/ClientCertificate 


I see this path here: https://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/v1/CertificateCollection_v1.xml
```
<String>
/redfish/v1/AccountService/MultiFactorAuth/ClientCertificate/Certificates
</String>
```
and the below paths at : https://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/v1/Certificate_v1.xml
```
<String>
/redfish/v1/AccountService/MultiFactorAuth/ClientCertificate/Certificates/{CertificateId}
</String>
```
Let me know if my explanation in the other comment explains this, if not, I can reply directly here.
